'''Mihira Bhoja''' (836–885 CE) or '''Bhoja I''' was a ruler of the [[Gurjara-Pratihara]] dynasty of [[India]]. He succeeded his father [[Ramabhadra]]. Bhoja was a devotee of [[Vishnu]] and adopted the title of ''Adivaraha'' which is inscribed on some of his coins.<ref>{{cite book|title=Medieval India: a textbook for classes XI-XII, Part 1|author=Satish Chandra, National Council of Educational Research and Training (India)|publisher=National Council of Educational Research and Training|year=1978|url=https://books.google.com/books?cd=7&id=tHVDAAAAYAAJ&dq=adivaraha+mihir+bhoj&q=adivaraha#search_anchor|page=9}}</ref> One of the outstanding political figures of India in ninth century, he ranks with [[Dhruva Dharavarsha]] and [[Dharmapala (emperor)|Dharmapala]] as a great general and empire builder.<ref name=""RSC_207">{{cite book
 | title =History of Ancient India: Earliest Times to 1000 A. D.  
 | author = Radhey Shyam Chaurasia  
 | publisher =Atlantic Publishers & Distributors
 | year =2002 
 | page =207 
 |isbn=978-81-269-0027-5| url  =https://books.google.com/books?id=cWmsQQ2smXIC&pg=PA207&dq
 | quote=He was undoubtedly one of the outstanding political figures of India in ninth century and ranks with Dhruva and Dharmapala as a great general and empire builder.
}}</ref>

At its height, Bhoja's empire extended to [[Narmada River]] in the South, [[Sutlej|Sutlej River]] in the northwest, and up to [[Bengal]] in the east. It extended over a large area from the foot of the [[Himalayas]] up to the river [[Narmada River|Narmada]] and included the present district of [[Etawah]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref>[http://etawah.nic.in/gaz/2.htm E-gazeteer-History of Etawah district]</ref><ref>[http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/schwartzberg/pager.html?object=068 Digital South Asia Library]</ref>

== Reign ==
{{multiple image|perrow=3|total_width=400|caption_align=center
| align    = left
| image1 = Sculptures near Teli Mandir, Gwalior Fort.jpg|caption1=Sculptures near [[Teli ka Mandir]], [[Gwalior Fort]].
| image2 = Gate of Teki Mandir, Gwalior Fort.jpg|caption2=Gate of Teli ka Mandir, Gwalior Fort.
| image3 = Teli ka mandir fort Gwalior - panoramio - Gyanendrasinghchauha… (1).jpg|caption3=[[Teli ka Mandir]] is a Hindu Temple built by Mihira Bhoja.<ref name="Bajpai2006">{{cite book|author=K. D. Bajpai|title=History of Gopāchala|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q3KcwLKuRnYC&pg=PA31|year=2006|publisher=Bharatiya Jnanpith|isbn=978-81-263-1155-2|page=31}}</ref>
}}
During his reign, the capital was in [[Kannauj]] (present-day [[Uttar Pradesh]]), during his period Kannauj was referred as [[Panchala]].

He was a bitter enemy of the [[Arab]] invaders<ref name=""RSC_207"/> who, according to an Arab chronicler, [[Sulaiman (chronicler)|Sulaiman]], maintained a large army and had a fine cavalry.<ref name=""RSC_207"/> The territories under his rule were prosperous and safe from robbers. His state was rich in natural resources, especially gold and silver mines.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}

Many temples made by him still survive. Teli Mandir, near [[Gwalior]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], marks the presence of [[Vishnu]] on  earth. The temple's architecture, design and layout features an outstanding fusion of architectural styles: the roof resembles a Dravidian style while the decoration highlights the art of North India.

He was succeeded by his son [[Mahendrapala I]] (c.836 - 910 CE).

== Military career ==
When Mihira Bhoja started his career reverses and defeats suffered by his father Ramabhadra had considerably lowered the prestige of the Royal [[Gurjara Pratihara]] family. He invaded the [[Pala Empire]] of [[Bengal]], but was defeated by [[Devapala (Pala dynasty)|Devapala]].<ref name=""RSC_207"/> He then launched a campaign to conquer the territories to the south of his empire and was successful. After Devapala's death, Bhoja defeated the [[Pala Empire|Pala]] King [[Narayanapala]] and the [[Rashtrakuta]] ruler [[Krishna II]].<ref name=Sen>Sen, S.N., 2013, A Textbook of Medieval Indian History, Delhi: Primus Books, {{ISBN|9789380607344}}</ref>{{rp|20–21}}  He gradually rebuilt the empire by conquest of territories in [[Rajasthan]], [[Gujarat]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]]. The [[Chandela]]s of [[Bundelkhand]] acknowledged his suzerainty.<ref name=""RSC_207"/> Besides being a conqueror, Bhoja was a great diplomat.<ref name=""RSC_207"/>
According to the sources (inscriptions found in Gawilor)  Mihira Bhoja defeated [[Dharmapala]]  the ruler of [[Pala Empire]]. But defeated by his son [[Devapala (Pala dynasty)|Devapala]]. There are other sources which claims that  Mihira Bhoja defeated some of the [[Arab]]  rulers  of the northwest.{{cn|date=May 2018}}

==Coins of Mihira Bhoja==
[[File:Pratihara bhoja.JPG|thumb|left|''Adivaraha Dramma'' coin, circa 836 - 885 CE]]

Mihira Bhoja's epithet was ''[[Varaha|Srimad-Adivaraha]]'' (the  fortunate primeval boar incarnation of [[Vishnu]]) and therefore there is a broad agreement amongst the scholars on the attribution of ''adivaraha dramma'' billon coins to him. These coins have a depiction of ''Adivaraha'' on the obverse.<ref>{{harvnb|Deyell|1999|pp=28–29}}</ref>

