[[File:Tonkawa chiefs.jpg|thumb|260px|Tonkawa (1898) survivors and descendants of massacre survivors. Standing L-R, Winnie Richards, John Rush Buffalo, William Stevens, John Allen, and Mary Richards. Photograph by [[Frank Rinehart]].]]
The '''Tonkawa massacre''' (October 23–24, 1862) occurred after an attack at the Confederate held Wichita Agency, located at [[Fort Sill]] near [[Anadarko, Oklahoma|Anadarko]] in [[Oklahoma]], when a force of pro-Union tribes attacked the agency, home to 300 members of the [[Tonkawa]], a tribe sympathetic to the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]]. During the attack on the Confederate held agency, the Confederate Indian agent Matthew Leeper and several other whites were killed.{{efn|Another source states that Leeper was not killed during this attack, but escaped unnoticed.<ref name="Chapter9">[oklahomathesoonerstate.com/materials/pdf%20book/Chapter%2009.pdf| Oklahoma the Sooner State, Chapter 9. Accessed October 2, 2016.</ref>}} In response to this attack the Tonkawa fled southward toward Confederate held [[Fort Arbuckle (Oklahoma)|Fort Arbuckle]], before they could reach the safety of the fort they were caught on October 24. In the resulting massacre, the estimates of Tonkawa dead are 137 men, women and children among them Chief Ha-shu-ka-na ("Can't Kill Him"), the Tonkawa were roasted alive and eaten by the ruthless Comanche.<ref>''Handbook of North American Indians: Plains'' By Raymond DeMallie, William Sturtevant p. 955</ref><ref>''Contrary Neighbors: Southern Plains and Removed Indians in Indian Territory''. By David La Vere p. 171</ref> There are varying accounts of the tribes involved in the massacre with the [[Osage Nation|Osage]], [[Shawnee]], [[Caddo]], [[Comanche]], [[Kiowa]], [[Wichita people|Wichita]] and [[Seminole]] being named in some accounts.<ref>''Historical atlas of Oklahoma''. By Charles Robert Goins, Danney Goble, John Wesley Morris p. 87</ref>
The reasons for the attack are varied with some suggesting that the Tonkawa had killed and eaten two Shawnees, and that they were responsible for the death and dismemberment of a young Caddo boy, as the Tonkawa were rumored to be cannibalistic. Other accounts name the main reason as their being allied to the southern cause. The relations between the Tonkawa and neighboring tribes had been antagonistic for years for a variety of reasons including the Tonkawa acting as scouts for the [[Texas Ranger Division|Texas Rangers]], and fighting alongside them in actions against hostile tribes including the Comanche.
Many of the survivors fled to Confederate held Fort Arbuckle after the massacre, base of the pro-Confederate [[Confederate units of Indian Territory#Chickasaw Nation|Chickasaw Battalion]], then made their way to Confederate-held, [[Fort Belknap (Texas)|Fort Belknap]] in Texas in 1863.<ref>Jeffrey D. Carlisle, "TONKAWA INDIANS," ''[[Handbook of Texas Online]]'' [https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/bmt68], accessed July 08, 2012. Published by the Texas State Historical Association.</ref> The massacre completely demoralized and fractured the remnants of the tribe, who remained without a leader and lived in squalor by Fort Belknap.<ref>''The Indians of Texas: From Prehistoric to Modern Times''. By W. W. Newcomb p. 359</ref> The remnants of the tribe then lived near Fort Griffin in Texas until 1884. They were then forced by the government to relocate temporarily to the Sac-Fox agency and then in the spring of 1885 to [[Fort Oakland]], occupied by Chief Joseph's Band of [[Nez Perce tribe|Nez Perce]] from 1878 to 1885. In 1891, 73 members of the Tonkawa were allocated {{convert|994.33|acre|km2}} of federal trust land, with an additional {{convert|238.24|acre|km2}} in individual allotments, near the former Fort Oakland, which is today [[Tonkawa, Oklahoma]], {{convert|12|mi|km}} west of [[Ponca City]]. The population on the reservation is 537 with 481 being officially on the tribal rolls.<ref>[http://www.tonkawatribe.com/profile/profile.htm The Tonkawa Tribe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110309213811/http://www.tonkawatribe.com/profile/profile.htm |date=2011-03-09 }}</ref>
